.TH WITR 1 "December 2025" "witr 1.0" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
witr \- explain why a process, service, or port is running

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B witr
[-i] [--pid N | --port N | name] [--short] [--tree] [--json] [--warnings] [--no-color] [--env] [--help] [--version]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B witr
is a Linux tool to explain why a process, service, or port is running, showing ancestry, context, supervisor, health, restarts, and warnings in a clear, colorized output. It also includes an interactive TUI mode.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-i, \-\-interactive
Start the interactive TUI mode to monitor TCP/UDP connections and processes.
.TP
.B --pid <n>
Explain a specific PID.
.TP
.B --port <n>
Explain port usage.
.TP
.B --short
One-line summary.
.TP
.B --tree
Show full process ancestry tree.
.TP
.B --json
Output result as JSON.
.TP
.B --warnings
Show only warnings.
.TP
.B --no-color
Disable colorized output.
.TP
.B --env
Show only environment variables for the process.
.TP
.B --help
Show the help message.
.TP
.B --version
Show version and exit.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B witr --pid 1234
.TP
.B witr --port 8080
.TP
.B witr nginx
.TP
.B witr nginx --short
.TP
.B witr --port 8080 --json

